Breast cancer histology in Caucasians, African Americans, Hispanics, Asians, and 
Pacific Islanders.

Klonoff-Cohen HS(1), Schaffroth LB, Edelstein SL, Molgaard C, Saltzstein SL.

Author information:
(1)Department of Family and Preventive Medicine, University of California, 
School of Medicine, San Diego, La Jolla 92093-0607, USA.

STUDY OBJECTIVES: To investigate the association between race/ethnicity and 
histologic types of breast cancer.
DESIGN: Cross-sectional study.
SETTING: Population-based data from the Northern California Tumor Registry, 
which is part of the National Cancer Institute's Surveillance, Epidemiology and 
End Results Program.
PARTICIPANTS: A total of 2759 breast cancer cases diagnosed in 1988.
MAIN RESULTS: Tumors were classified as ductal, lobular, and mixed/unspecified 
carcinoma. Ductal carcinoma was the most common (83.6%) and lobular carcinoma 
was the rarest. Most cases were diagnosed in the localized stage (56.3%). 
Caucasian women had the highest rates of total breast cancer (240.9/100,000), 
